5\n* [[Briana Younger]] \u2013 reporter, 2019\u20132020\n* [[Olimpia Zagnolia]] \u2013 illustrator, 2018\n* [[Oussama Zahr]] \u2013 reporter, 2018\u20132020\n* [[Daniel Zalewski]] \u2013 features editor and non\u2013fiction writer\n* [[Zha Jianying]] \u2013 writer, 2010\n* [[Jack Ziegler]] \u2013 cartoonist, 2013\u20132019\n* [[Katherine Zoepf]] \u2013 writer, 2013\n}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{float|[[#Top|Return to TOC]]}}\n{{Reflist}}\n[[Category:The New Yorker people|*List]]\n", "name_user": "Sunwin1960", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eG", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_The_New_Yorker_contributors"}
{"title_page": "The Jones Girls", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = The Jones Girls\n| background          = group_or_band\n| image               =  \n| image_size          = \n| caption             = \n| alias               = \n| origin              = [[Detroit, Michigan]], [[United States]]\n| genre               = {{hlist|[[Rhythm and blues|R&B]]|[[Soul music|soul]]|[[Philadelphia soul]]}}\n| instrument          = Vocals\n| years_active        = 1970\u20131993 \n| label               = {{hlist|GM Records|[[Philadelphia International]]|[[RCA Records|RCA]]|ARP}}\n| associated_acts     = {{hlist|[[McFadden & Whitehead]]|[[Gamble & Huff]]|[[The Emotions]]}}\n| website             = \n| past_members     = Brenda Jones <small>(deceased)</small><br/>[[Shirley Jones (R&B singer)|Shirley Jones]]<br/>Valorie Jones <small>(deceased)</small>\n}}\n'''The Jones Girls''' were an American [[R&B]] vocal trio of sisters from [[Detroit, Michigan]], United States. Consisting of Brenda, [[Shirley Jones (R&B singer)|Shirley]] and Valorie Jones, The Jones Girls first signed and recorded for GM Records in 1970. The trio were best known for their singles during the late\u20131970s through the 1980s; most notably 1979's \"You Gonna Make Me Love Somebody Else\". After a six\u2013year tenure with GM, they then recorded for [[Philadelphia International Records]] with [[Gamble & Huff]].\n\n==History==\nThe group consisted of sisters Brenda (December 7, 1954 \u2013 April 3, 2017),<ref>[http://www.pippinfuneralhome.com/notices/Brenda-Williams Brenda Jones Williams December 7, 1954 \u2013 April 3, 2017 (age 62)]</ref><ref>[https://newsone.com/3704182/brenda-jones-62-the-jones-girls-rip/ NewsOne - Brenda Jones 62, The Jones Girls - RIP - April 3, 2017]</ref> Valorie (April 17, 1956 \u2013 December 2, 2001) and [[Shirley Jones (R&B singer)|Shirley Jones]] (born September 22, 1953). They performed as backup singers for [[Lou Rawls]], [[Teddy Pendergrass]], [[Aretha Franklin]], and Le Pamplemousse. They worked with [[Diana Ross]] from 1975\u201378 and were the backup singers on [[Linda Clifford]]'s 1978 album ''[[If My Friends Could See Me Now (Linda Clifford album)|If My Friends Could See Me Now]]''. They also performed on [[Tower of Power]]'s disco-themed 1979 album ''[[Back on the Streets (Tower of Power album)|Back on the Streets]]''. Their biggest hit was \"You Gonna Make Me Love Somebody Else\". The song hit the [[Billboard Magazine]] Top 40 at number 38 in May 1979. The song was also a Top 5 R&B hit. It became a [[Music recording sales certification|gold record]]. An additional hit followed in 1980, with the single \"I Just Love The Man\", charting at number 9 in January 1981. The less successful \"Nights Over Egypt\" (1981), written by [[Dexter Wansel]], charted at R&B #23 in 1982.\n\nAfter the release and failure of their fourth U.S. album, ''On Target'', lead singer Shirley Jones pursued a solo career and had a number 1 R&B hit on Billboard with \"[[Do You Get Enough Love]]\", from her top-ten debut album ''Always in the Mood'' (1986). \"Do You Get Enough Love\" was written by [[Bunny Sigler]] who also produced it with [[Kenny Gamble]].<ref>{{cite book |title= The Billboard Book of Number One Rhythm & Blues Hits|last=White |first=Adam |last2=Bronson |first2=Fred|authorlink2=Fred Bronson |year=1993 |publisher=Billboard Books:Watson-Guptill Publications, New York |page=368}}</ref> Valorie Jones died on December 2, 2001, in Detroit, Michigan, at the age of 45.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=7742025|title=Valorie Jones (1956 - 2001) - Find A Grave Memorial|website=Findagrave.com|accessdate=1 May 2017}}</ref> In 2007, Shirley Jones released an album ''Ladies Night Out'' together with [[Jean Carn]] and [[Cherrelle]], on CD and DVD.\n\nBrenda eventually moved to Atlanta, where she sang frequently with her four-piece band, performing both jazz and R&B numbers, including many Jones Girls' tunes. She later moved to New York after her children were grown, to have a more active performing and recording schedule. On April 3, 2017, she was visiting her daughter in [[Wilmington, Delaware]], and was hit by several cars and killed while attempting to cross the street. She was 62.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ebony.com/entertainment-culture/brenda-jones-jones-girls-died#axzz4dRZYlFVk|title=Singer Brenda Jones, of the R&B Group The Jones Girls, Has Passed Away - EBONY|website=Ebony.com|accessdate=1 May 2017}}</ref> Shirley continues to perform successfully as The Jones Girls with two of her nieces and a nephew on background vocals.\n\n==Covers==\n\"[[Who Can I Run To]]\", from the band's self-titled 1979 debut album, was covered by [[Xscape (band)|Xscape]] in 1995. Their cover version became a number 1 R&B and number 8 pop hit. The original version was the B-side of \"You Gonna Make Me Love Somebody Else\".\n\nNights Over Egypt was covered by [[Incognito (band)|Incognito]] in their album No Time Like The Future and by [[Dexter Wansel]] in 2019.\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n! colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Record Label\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n! width=\"35\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br><ref name=\"allumic\">{{cite magazine|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p4628|pure_url=yes}}|title=US Charts > The Jones Girls|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2014-03-15}}</ref>\n! width=\"35\"| [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|US<br>R&B]]<br><ref name=\"allumic\"/>\n|-\n| 1979\n| align=\"left\"|  ''[[The Jones Girls (album)|The Jones Girls]]'' \n| 50\n| 8\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[Philadelphia International Records|Philadelphia International]]\n|-\n| 1980\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[At Peace with Woman]]''\n| 96\n| 7\n|-\n| 1981\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[Get as Much Love as You Can]]''\n| 155\n| 25\n|-\n| 1983\n| align=\"left\"|  ''On Target''\n| &mdash;\n| 59\n| rowspan=\"1\"| [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n|-\n| 1984\n| align=\"left\"| ''Keep It Comin'''\n| 201\n| &mdash;\n| rowspan=\"1\"| Philadelphia International\n|-\n| 1992\n| align=\"left\"| ''Coming Back''\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| rowspan=\"1\"| ARP\n|-\n| colspan=\"15\" style=\"font-size:90%\" | \"\u2014\" denotes a recording that did not chart or was not released in that territory.\n|}\n\n===Compilation albums===\n*''The Best of the Jones Girls'' (2000, [[The Right Stuff Records|The Right Stuff]])\n*''Keeping up with the Joneses: The Early Years'' (2000, [[Sanctuary Records Group|Sequel UK]])\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! colspan=\"4\"| Peak chart positions\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n! width=\"35\"| [[Billboard Hot 100|US]]<br><ref name=\"allumic\"/>\n! width=\"35\"| [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|US<br>R&B]]<br><ref name=\"allumic\"/>\n! width=\"35\"| [[Hot Dance Club Play|US<br>Dan]]<br><ref name=\"allumic\"/>\n! width=\"35\"| [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|US<br>A/C]]<br><ref name=\"allumic\"/>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1970\n| align=\"left\"| \"My Own Special Way\"\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1972\n| align=\"left\"| \"Come Back\"\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n|-\n| align=\"left\"| \"Your Love Controls Me\"\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1973\n| align=\"left\"| \"Taster of the Honey (Not the Keeper of the Bee)\"\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1974\n| align=\"left\"| \"If You Don't Love Me No More\"\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n|-\n| align=\"left\"| \"Will You Be There\"\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1975\n| align=\"left\"| \"I Turn to You\"\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n|-\n| align=\"left\"| \"Hey Lucinda\"\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1979\n| align=\"left\"| \"You Gonna Make Me Love Somebody Else\"\n| 38\n| 5\n| 12\n| &mdash;\n|-\n| align=\"left\"| \"We're a Melody\"\n| &mdash;\n| 78\n| &mdash;\n| 50\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1980\n| align=\"left\"| \"I'm at Your Mercy\"\n| &mdash;\n| 77\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n|-\n| align=\"left\"| \"Dance Turned into a Romance\"\n| &mdash;\n| 22\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n|-\n| align=\"left\"| \"I Just Love the Man\"\n| &mdash;\n| 9\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1981\n| align=\"left\"| \"Back in the Day\"\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n|-\n| align=\"left\"| \"(I Found) That Man of Mine\"\n| &mdash;\n| 20\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1981\n| align=\"left\"| \"Nights Over Egypt\"\n| &mdash;\n| 23\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n|-\n| align=\"left\"| \"Get as Much Love as You Can\"\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1983\n| align=\"left\"| \"On Target\" \n| &mdash;\n| 43\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n|-\n| align=\"left\"| \"2 Win U Back\"\n| &mdash;\n| 47\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 1984\n| align=\"left\"| \"Better Things to Do\"\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1992\n| align=\"left\"| \"Sweet Ecstasy\"\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n|-\n| align=\"left\"| \"You Threw Our Love Away\"\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n| &mdash;\n|-\n| colspan=\"15\" style=\"font-size:90%\" | \"\u2014\" denotes a recording that did not chart or was not released in that territory.\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-jones-girls-mn0000825168 Allmusic profile of The Jones Girls]\n*[http://www.soultracks.com/jones_girls.htm Soul Tracks profile of The Jones Girls]\n*[{{BillboardURLbyName|artist=the jones girls|bio=true}} Billboard profile of The Jones Girls]\n*[http://www.soulwalking.co.uk/Jones%20Girls.html Soul Walking profile of